,"1131":"1131","1152":"1152","1174":"1174","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1136":"1136","1125":"1125","1089":"1089","1166":"1166","1199":"1199","about 1125":"about 1125","Kedleston, Bepler, Derbyshire, England":"Kedleston, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"CURZON","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Notre-Dame-de-Courson in Calvados, France, which was named with the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Curtius</i> (from <i>curtus</i> ‘short’) + the locative suffix <i>-o</i>, genitive <i>-onis</i>. There is also a place called Curzon in Vendée, but this is not the source of the English surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Curson","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Curzon  ."]}]},{"name":"Sybil","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Sybilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sibilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sybille","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Sybil</b> ."]},{"name":"Sibella","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sybil CURZON DECURZON was born in 1150, in England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert de Curzon, was 61 and her mother, Beatrix d'Aufay, was 71. She had at least 2 sons with Thomas de Curzon. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1150–":"1150–Surnud","1125–1199":"1125–1199","1131–Male":"1131–Surnud","1136–1174":"1136–1174","1150–Female":"1150–Surnud","–1166":"–1166","1152–Male":"1152–Surnud","1187–Male":"1187–Surnud","1186–1242":"1186–1242","1089–1150":"1089–1150","1080–1160":"1080–1160","1080":"1080","1187":"1187","1242":"1242","1186":"1186","1131":"1131","1152":"1152","1174":"1174","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1136":"1136","1125":"1125","1089":"1089","1166":"1166","1199":"1199","about 1125":"umbes 1125","Kedleston, Bepler, Derbyshire, England"